'Formic acid' (also called 'methanoic acid') is the simplest carboxylic acid.
Its chemical formula is HCOOH or HCO 2H. It is an important
intermediate in chemical synthesis and occurs naturally, most notably in the
venom of bee and ant stings. In fact, its name comes from the Latin word for
ant, [[formica]], referring to its early isolation by the distillation of ant
bodies. Esters, salts, and the anion derived from formic acid are referred to
as formates.
